---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Eyebrow from '../components/Eyebrow.astro';
import PostCard from '../components/PostCard.astro';
import Rebuttal from '../components/Rebuttal.astro';
import { withBase } from '../site';

const postParagraphs = [
  'Is the hype around the so called ‘mega tip’ real?',
  'Firstly, what is a mega tip? A regional waste facility in our LGA would take about 60,000 tonnes per year, from four neighbouring councils, if they enter into a partnership, whilst metro landfills take over 200,000 tonnes every year, many of which are in residential areas.',
  'The science and regulations in NSW behind new landfill is the strictest in the country. It is sad that some elected officials have already closed their minds to options to deal with our waste. How can councillors make informed and educated decisions in the best interests of our whole LGA if some are already actively campaigning against a potential site without even being prepared to support the studies to determine viability.',
  'The reality is that we need a solution. And we need to do the research. That is the responsible thing to do. Traffic impact, environmental reports and feasibility studies need to be completed. Is Blakebrook suitable? We simply cannot make an informed decision until these studies are done. These are responsible generational decisions that most councillors are prepared to make.',
  'The hype of 400 truck movements per day, waterways being contaminated, environmental impacts being devastated is unknown until further research is done.',
  'Personally, I am going to keep an open mind as all councillors should.',
  'The image attached is the technology that is required to create a new landfill. Not as simple as digging a hole and burying waste!',
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Breaking down the mayor's post"
  description="A line-by-line read of Mayor Steve Krieg's public Facebook post on the proposed Blakebrook landfill: what holds up, what's reasonable, and where reassurance stands in for evidence."
  progress
  article
>
  <header class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-5 pt-14 sm:pt-20">
    <Eyebrow>Reading the case in context</Eyebrow>
    <h1
      class="mt-4 max-w-[18ch] font-display text-4xl font-extrabold leading-[1.04] tracking-[-0.02em] text-ink sm:text-6xl"
    >
      Breaking down the mayor's post
    </h1>
    <p class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-lg leading-relaxed text-ink-soft">
      Much of the public case for the proposed Blakebrook landfill was made in a
      single Facebook post by Lismore mayor Steve Krieg. It is reproduced in full
      below, then read line by line. Where the reasoning holds, we say so; where
      reassurance stands in for evidence, we show why.
    </p>
  </header>

  <!-- The post, in context: actual screenshot + re-typeset, side by side -->
  <section class="mx-auto max-w-6xl px-5 pt-12">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <figure class="shot">
        <img
          src={withBase('/media/krieg-post-full.jpg')}
          width="470"
          height="960"
          alt="Screenshot of Mayor Steve Krieg's public Facebook post about the proposed regional waste facility."
          loading="lazy"
        />
        <figcaption>The post as published &mdash; public Facebook post, 2025.</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <div class="retype">
        <PostCard
          author="Steve Krieg"
          role="Mayor, Lismore City Council"
          source="Public Facebook post, 2025"
          paragraphs={postParagraphs}
          attachment="Attached to the post: a generic infographic titled &ldquo;Anatomy of a Landfill and Resource Recovery Facility.&rdquo; We discuss it below but do not reproduce it."
        />

        <aside class="infographic-note">
          <p class="ino-label">About that attached image</p>
          <p>
            The picture the post calls &ldquo;the technology that is
            required&rdquo; is a glossy, generic infographic &mdash; an American
            &ldquo;Anatomy of a Landfill <em>and Resource Recovery
            Facility</em>&rdquo; promotional graphic. It is not an engineering
            plan for Blakebrook: not its geology, not its catchment, not its
            design. No design for Blakebrook has been published. A borrowed,
            out-of-region illustration is being used to suggest the technology is
            settled and the question answered.
          </p>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Line by line -->
  <section class="mx-auto max-w-6xl px-5 pt-16 pb-8">
    <div class="lbl-head">
      <span class="lbl-kicker">Line by line</span>
      <h2 class="lbl-h">Seven sentences, weighed</h2>
      <div class="lbl-rule" aria-hidden="true"></div>
    </div>

    <div class="breakdown">
      <Rebuttal
        n="01"
        verdict="Wrong yardstick"
        tone="spin"
        quote="A regional waste facility in our LGA would take about 60,000 tonnes per year… whilst metro landfills take over 200,000 tonnes every year, many of which are in residential areas."
        link={{ href: '/numbers', label: 'See the tonnage comparison' }}
      >
        <p>
          Tonnage is not the test of whether a site is safe. A smaller load in a
          high-rainfall, flood-influenced catchment can carry more risk than a
          much larger one on a dry, deep-watertable site. Comparing raw tonnes
          against Sydney landfills tells you nothing about whether
          <strong>Blakebrook</strong> is suitable &mdash; it just makes the
          number sound small.
        </p>
      </Rebuttal>

      <Rebuttal
        n="02"
        verdict="Reassurance by assertion"
        tone="spin"
        quote="The science and regulations in NSW behind new landfill is the strictest in the country."
        link={{ href: '/numbers', label: 'How liner life depends on heat' }}
      >
        <p>
          Strict rules lower risk; they do not zero it. Engineered liners have a
          service life that shortens as temperature rises, and protection depends
          on decades of monitoring, maintenance and enforcement. &ldquo;Strictest
          in the country&rdquo; is an assurance, not a guarantee that this site,
          built and maintained over fifty years, will not fail.
        </p>
      </Rebuttal>

      <Rebuttal
        n="03"
        verdict="Reframes scrutiny"
        tone="unsupported"
        quote="It is sad that some elected officials have already closed their minds… actively campaigning against a potential site without even being prepared to support the studies to determine viability."
        link={{ href: '/critique', label: 'On process and framing' }}
      >
        <p>
          Questioning a site &mdash; and asking whether public money should be
          spent investigating it &mdash; is part of due process, not a closed
          mind. This framing casts scrutiny as irresponsibility. People can
          support good waste decisions <em>and</em> doubt that this particular
          quarry is the right place, without being accused of obstruction.
        </p>
      </Rebuttal>

      <Rebuttal
        n="04"
        verdict="Reasonable, as far as it goes"
        tone="fair"
        quote="We need to do the research… We simply cannot make an informed decision until these studies are done."
        link={{ href: '/proposal', label: "What's actually proposed" }}
      >
        <p>
          This part is fair. Traffic, environmental and feasibility studies
          <em>should</em> precede any decision, and saying so is responsible. The
          live community concern is the reverse risk &mdash; that a site is
          effectively chosen, and the public brought along, before genuine
          consultation has happened.
        </p>
      </Rebuttal>

      <Rebuttal
        n="05"
        verdict="Can't be hype and an open question at once"
        tone="spin"
        quote="The hype of 400 truck movements per day, waterways being contaminated… is unknown until further research is done. Personally, I am going to keep an open mind."
        link={{ href: '/numbers', label: 'The real truck math' }}
      >
        <p>
          You cannot label the community's concerns &ldquo;hype&rdquo; in one
          breath and claim an open mind in the next. On the trucks specifically,
          the honest figure is neither 400 nor zero &mdash; roughly 30&ndash;50
          movements a day, a real local change worth assessing. Waterway risk in a
          high-rainfall catchment is a legitimate question, not hype.
        </p>
      </Rebuttal>

      <Rebuttal
        n="06"
        verdict="Borrowed reassurance"
        tone="spin"
        quote="The image attached is the technology that is required to create a new landfill. Not as simple as digging a hole and burying waste!"
        link={{ href: '/proposal', label: 'What we actually know' }}
      >
        <p>
          The attached image is a generic, out-of-region promotional infographic
          &mdash; not a plan for Blakebrook. Showing a polished picture of an
          idealised facility implies the engineering is decided and the risks
          handled. They are not: no Blakebrook design exists yet. A picture is
          standing in for a plan that hasn't been made.
        </p>
      </Rebuttal>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .post-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 360px minmax(0, 1fr);
    gap: 40px;
    align-items: start;
  }
  .shot {
    margin: 0;
    position: sticky;
    top: 88px;
  }
  .shot img {
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    border-radius: 14px;
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    box-shadow: var(--shadow);
    display: block;
  }
  .shot figcaption {
    margin-top: 10px;
    font-family: 'IBM Plex Mono', monospace;
    font-size: 0.72rem;
    color: var(--muted);
  }
  .infographic-note {
    margin-top: 18px;
    padding: 18px 20px;
    background: var(--ink);
    color: var(--paper);
    border-radius: 14px;
  }
  .infographic-note p {
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: rgba(245, 244, 239, 0.82);
  }
  .ino-label {
    font-family: 'IBM Plex Mono', monospace;
    font-size: 0.72rem;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.14em;
    color: var(--brand-bright);
    margin-bottom: 8px;
  }
  .infographic-note em {
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--paper);
  }

  .lbl-head {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 18px;
    margin-bottom: 4px;
  }
  .lbl-kicker {
    font-family: 'IBM Plex Mono', monospace;
    font-size: 0.74rem;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.18em;
    color: var(--brand);
    flex: none;
  }
  .lbl-h {
    font-family: 'Archivo', sans-serif;
    font-weight: 800;
    font-size: clamp(1.6rem, 1.2rem + 1.6vw, 2.2rem);
    flex: none;
  }
  .lbl-rule {
    flex: 1 1 auto;
    height: 1px;
    background: var(--line);
  }

  @media (max-width: 860px) {
    .post-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: 28px;
    }
    .shot {
      position: static;
      max-width: 420px;
    }
    .lbl-head {
      flex-wrap: wrap;
      gap: 10px;
    }
    .lbl-rule {
      display: none;
    }
  }
</style>
